<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jerry Hicks and Mark I. Pinsky 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 ELECTION FEVER? Officials have tallied the final count on the number of 
registered voters for Tuesday's election: It's slightly higher than for the 
June primary, but below the 1992 fall numbers. Republicans are still well ahead 
of Democrats, by more than 200,000. . . . Where do all these voters live? 
Anaheim has the most, at 103,959. Huntington Beach is second at 103,363. And 
Santa Ana is No. 3 at 70,219. 
</P>
<P>
 SOURCE OF PAIN: The struggles of black football players is the subject of 
Sunday's "This Is the NFL" (Channel 11, 8:30 a.m.). The program notes that the 
Los Angeles Rams broke the color barrier in 1946 when Kenny Washington joined 
the team. . . . One poignant moment comes from Hall of Famer and current Rams 
broadcaster Deacon Jones: "Humiliation is walking past five upscale white 
schools and going to the little, old, black two-room shack down the street . . 
. They made you believe you were less than a man. So, you're constantly trying 
to prove yourself." 
</P>
<P>
 ECUMENICAL MISSION: Catholics founded Mission San Juan Capistrano. But today, 
the Catholic mission hosts 500 people from different religions for a diversity 
fair. It begins with a Jewish Sabbath Service. Workshops on Hindu, Buddhist, 
Bahai, Catholic and Protestant faiths will be offered. Preregistration interest 
was high for Islam and Muslims sessions. . . . Says mission administrator 
Gerald J. Miller: "If you wanted to know about them, where else would you go?" 
</P>
<P>
 MUSEUM BLUES: Most of the blues at art museums are in the hues of the artists' 
visions hanging on the walls. But tonight at the Fullerton Museum Center -- 
which emphasizes that it's more than an art museum -- there will be the blues 
you can tap your foot to. . . . Harmonica Fats and the Bernie Pearl Blues Band 
will play a sold-out gig in its auditorium. Says curator Lynn LaBat: "We do 
these things to draw people to see the museum, but we also want to add cultural 
value to the community." Final Tally 
</P>
<P>
 County registration for Tuesday's election is slightly down from the 1992 
presidential election. 
</P>
<P>
 1994: 1,170,072 
</P>
<P>
 1992: 1,240,778 
</P>
<P>
 1990: 1,090,954 
</P>
<P>
 1988: 1,183,166 
</P>
<P>
 1986: 1,090,137 
</P>
<P>
 Source: Orange County Registrar of Voters 
</P>
</TEXT>
