<HEADLINE>
<P>
POLICE FEAR PROP. 187 WILL CRUSH HARD-EARNED TRUST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PATRICK J. McDONNELL, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Albert Carretero didn't hesitate to stop by the sheriff's station on the 
Eastside last week to pick up some checks that had been stolen from him and 
recovered. 
</P>
<P>
 But after Tuesday, Carretero says, he will probably think twice about 
approaching police officers in California. 
</P>
<P>
 "Better I lose my checks than lose everything and get sent back to Mexico," 
Carretero, a 21-year-old undocumented produce salesman, said as he left the 
station, property in hand. "It's not worth it." 
</P>
<P>
 The widespread concern about the potential impact of Proposition 187 has 
focused on its best-known provisions, those denying illegal immigrants public 
education and other tax-supported benefits, including non-emergency health 
care. But in communities statewide, law enforcement authorities and residents 
are bracing for the potential fallout from another proposition mandate, one 
that could profoundly alter always delicate relations between officers and 
immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
 A section of Proposition 187 would require that police notify the U.S. 
Immigration and Naturalization Service of the identities of all arrestees 
suspected of being illegal immigrants. That measure, critics say, could 
endanger immigrant-police cooperation, eroding the hard-won trust of a 
population that is often naturally suspicious of the police, who frequently 
take on the role of oppressor in Mexico and Central America.  
</P>
<P>
 "I never trusted the police in Mexico," Rafael Angel Martinez, a 38-year-old 
laborer, said as he stood outside his Eastside apartment on Whittier Boulevard 
on a recent evening, "but here I have a lot more confidence in the police." 
</P>
<P>
 Moments earlier, Martinez had called deputies to report a theft from his 
apartment, located behind a shop on Whittier Boulevard. Two men, he said, had 
driven up and stolen a roll of carpet that he had left outside his door. 
</P>
<P>
 "They had no right to take it," Martinez said, adding that he had bought the 
roll at a bargain rate and hoped to install it in his threadbare flat, its 
windows and doors covered with security bars. 
</P>
<P>
 After making his report to deputies, Martinez told a reporter that he was an 
undocumented worker from Mexico. He and his wife illicitly entered the United 
States two years ago via Tijuana, he said, following the well-trodden path of 
many before him. 
</P>
<P>
 Would he have approached the officers if he thought they would inquire about 
his residency status? 
</P>
<P>
 "I probably would have," Martinez responded with a smile, "but I think I'd be 
one of the brave few." 
</P>
<P>
 Police fear that people such as Martinez might avoid contact with officers, 
even to report crimes. Officers also are wary of taking on additional tasks in 
a time of already tight budgets. 
</P>
<P>
 "Are we assuming the role of the INS?" asked Lt. Thomas Angel at the East Los 
Angeles sheriff's station, which polices a sprawling enclave inhabited by many 
immigrants, both documented and illegal. "We're asked to do a lot now, and if 
we're asked to do more it'll drain our resources." 
</P>
<P>
 Yet the official opposition to Proposition 187 -- voiced publicly by such law 
enforcement leaders as Los Angeles County Sheriff Sherman Block and Los Angeles 
Police Chief Willie L. Williams -- is far from unanimous among rank-and-file 
officers, reflecting the sharply divided sentiments of the public at large. 
</P>
<P>
 In the report room of the East Los Angeles sheriff's station last week, 
several deputies, speaking privately, voiced their personal opinions that 
Proposition 187 is long overdue, and would not be so burdensome to implement. 
</P>
<P>
 "We check people's driver's licenses. Why can't we check their other papers?" 
asked one deputy, a Latino, angered by what he said was a proliferation of 
illegal immigrants receiving welfare and other benefits. "My parents and 
grandparents came over for work. Now they come over for a free ride." 
</P>
<P>
 But a second Latino officer agreed with only part of his argument. He said 
illegal immigration must be curtailed, but contended that the proposed 
initiative is too harsh. 
</P>
<P>
 "People come here to work; they never heard about welfare until they got 
here," the officer said. "I just can't see kicking kids out of school and not 
giving them health care." 
</P>
<P>
 Nonetheless, the second deputy added: "I bet most cops are for Proposition 
187." 
</P>
<P>
 Speaking for the record, deputies on the Eastside interviewed last week 
generally said they were neutral on Proposition 187 or were inclined to vote 
against it, a stance that aligns them with the top brass. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's going to be a pain" to implement, said Deputy Jose Mejia, a seven-year 
veteran of the department and native of the same Eastside community that he now 
patrols. 
</P>
<P>
 However, Mejia said, officers are often caught in the middle of the 
contentious immigration debate: Legal residents criticize them for not doing 
enough about the sometimes-boisterous gatherings of day laborers and the 
proliferation of street vendors, while immigrant rights activists assail them 
for any crackdowns. 
</P>
<P>
 "We get caught between everything," Mejia said as he guided his patrol car 
down the streets of the neighborhood where he grew up, occasionally stopping to 
chat in Spanish and English with longtime acquaintances. "It can be really hard 
for us." 
</P>
<P>
 As he drove past street vendors hawking everything from tamales to sweaters, 
Mejia noted the dilemma: The vendors are illegal and, technically, subject to 
fines and confiscation of their goods. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm supposed to be doing something about that," Mejia said as he drove by one 
corner salesman. 
</P>
<P>
 But, he noted, in a high-crime, densely populated neighborhood where gang 
violence is endemic and police are relatively few, busting street vendors is 
often way down the priority list. Such is often the selective nature of 
policing an immigrant community, particularly one with a high undocumented 
population. The incidence of drivers lacking licenses is high on the Eastside 
and in other immigrant neighborhoods, officers said, especially since 
California began requiring proof of legal U.S. residency this year before 
issuing licenses. While technically required to cite unlicensed drivers and 
empowered to impound their cars, police say a more lenient approach often 
prevails. 
</P>
<P>
 "You've got to be flexible here; you've got to weigh the situation," one 
officer said. Even if Proposition 187 is approved, legal challenges are likely 
to test its law enforcement provisions. A state legislative report released 
last week concluded that requiring police to question arrestees about their 
residency status probably violates constitutional privacy laws. 
</P>
<P>
 If the proposition passes and is not thrown out in the courts, however, it 
will be left to counties and cities to find ways to put the requirements into 
effect. Experts cite several problematic areas, including the amorphous 
definition of who might be a "suspected" illegal immigrant. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't think they'll let us stop someone just because it looks like they're 
fresh from the border," said one sheriff's deputy, who was responding one night 
last week to a shooting on the Eastside.  
</P>
<P>
 Another hurdle, lawyers say, is defining who exactly is considered an 
arrestee, the only people who would be questioned about their status under the 
proposition. As Police Chief Williams has noted, even someone stopped for a 
traffic citation might be technically considered subject to such interrogation. 
</P>
<P>
 In the streets here and elsewhere, there is uneasiness, both among the 
law-abiding residents and the plethora of vendors, day laborers, false-document 
salesmen and others who engage in a thriving, if sometimes illegal, commerce.  
</P>
<P>
 "Right now I get along fine with the police, but I think that might change if 
they started stopping people for papers," said Luis Jaime Lugo, a 19-year-old 
native of Mexico who was selling tacos from his stand in East Los Angeles. 
"People would be scared." 
</P>
<P>
 Requiring police to check the residence status of detainees would alter years 
of limited cooperation between many local law enforcement authorities and the 
INS, a separation often achieved through lawsuits and vociferous protests. 
Immigrant rights monitors say the LAPD has strong policies that, for instance, 
restrict officers from questioning people simply because of their immigration 
status. Other departments put no limits on such questioning. 
</P>
<P>
 To be sure, even in Los Angeles, relations between police and immigrants are 
often far from smooth: Activists from groups such as El Rescate, the Central 
American refugee organization based in the Pico-Union district, frequently 
accuse police of wrongly asking suspects for their residence documents. During 
the 1992 riots, the LAPD turned over hundreds of suspected illegal immigrants 
to the INS. 
</P>
<P>
 However, most immigrants seem to separate street cops from the long-dreaded 
INS, a benefit to police who rely on all residents to report crimes, provide 
witness statements and otherwise assist authorities. 
</P>
<P>
 "To me, police are here to protect us, not to ask us about our documents," 
said Leticia Sanchez, a 30-year-old mother of four from Mexico who was among 
the customers at Lugo's taco stand. "People will run away from police if they 
start asking for papers." 
</P>
<P>
 * WALKOUTS DECRIED: Officials deny aiding school walkouts over Prop. 187. A24 
</P>
<P>
 * RELATED STORIES: A24-25 
</P>
</TEXT>
