<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHIRAC TO SEEK FRENCH PRESIDENCY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Mayor Jacques Chirac declared his candidacy for president Friday, intensifying 
the kind of struggle on the right that led to a Socialist victory in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
 The bid intensifies a bitter duel between Chirac and Prime Minister Edouard 
Balladur, both members of the conservative Rally for the Republic party, to 
represent the right in the two-round elections in April and May. 
</P>
<P>
 Balladur's enormous popularity since becoming prime minister in April, 1993, 
has eroded in recent weeks over scandals in his Cabinet and stubbornly high 
unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
 Chirac, 61, is considered slightly more conservative than Balladur, 65. But 
both are likely to push ahead selling off state companies and trimming social 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
 The Socialists are banking on rising voter discontent with unemployment, which 
rose 0.1% this week to 12.7%, and with scandals now claiming members of 
Balladur's Cabinet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
