<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: CITY GUIDE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 LAKE FOREST 
</P>
<P>
 Mayor: Marcia Rudolph 
</P>
<P>
 Age: 53 
</P>
<P>
 Occupation: Teacher 
</P>
<P>
 First elected: March, 1991 
</P>
<P>
 Term expires: This month 
</P>
<P>
 Key issues: Wants the city to enhance public services, such as police, parks 
development and city maintenance. Expand city recreation programs. Favors a 
continued proactive approach to El Toro Marine Corps Air Station reuse plan. 
(The base is scheduled to close at the end of the decade. The city is working 
with county officials to craft a redevelopment plan for the land.) Reuse ideas 
for the base range from building an air cargo facility there to converting it 
into a commercial district. Lake Forest and other South County cities are 
against converting the base into an airport, fearing the traffic, noise and 
environmental effects. Measure A on the ballot Tuesday asks voters if they want 
to build an airport at El Toro. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Councilman: Richard T. Dixon 
</P>
<P>
 Age: 46 
</P>
<P>
 Occupation: Health insurance salesman 
</P>
<P>
 First elected: March, 1991 
</P>
<P>
 Term expires: This month 
</P>
<P>
 Key issues: Wants to establish the city on a strong financial footing and 
minimize the growing pains that some older cities have experienced. Wants to 
make sure Lake Forest can always deliver public safety services, such as police 
and fire. Opposed to converting the El Toro Marine Corps Air Station into an 
international airport, as some cities such as Newport Beach have suggested. 
(Lake Forest is just south of the base and is considered one of the cities that 
would be most affected by what is built there, once the Marines pull out at the 
end of the decade.) 
</P>
<P>
 * 
