<HEADLINE>
<P>
JUDGE MAY LIFT BAN FOR JURORS' LIST OF TV SHOWS; SIMPSON CASE: HOME SHOPPING 
NETWORK LEADS PANEL'S REQUEST, ALONG WITH 'STAR TREK,' 'MELROSE PLACE' AND 
FOOTBALL. STATIONS AGREE TO PROVIDE EDITED MATERIAL. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ANDREA FORD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Judge Lance A. Ito had the "MacNeil/Lehrer News-Hour" in mind, but the jurors 
in the O.J. Simpson case are thinking Home Shopping Network. 
</P>
<P>
 The popular cable TV marketplace topped a list of shows the jurors want to see 
next week, when Ito is expected to relax his order barring them from exposure 
to all television, radio, magazines, newspapers and bookstores. 
</P>
<P>
 Also on the list was one local news show -- KTLA's "News at 10." One would 
think a nightly news broadcast has as much chance of making the cut as, say, 
Fox's upcoming O.J. Simpson movie. 
</P>
<P>
 But that may not be the case. 
</P>
<P>
 After Ito met Friday with a Simpson prosecutor and a member of the defense 
team, all parties tentatively agreed that jurors could watch edited versions of 
news programs. 
</P>
<P>
 It is likely the panel also will be able to watch tapes of most of the 
television shows they want -- with the commercial breaks edited out -- as well 
as receive newspapers a day late with reports on the Simpson excised. 
</P>
<P>
 Radio would continue to be banned under the tentative agreement because that 
is not considered a hardship, said defense lawyer Shawn Chapman. 
</P>
<P>
 The jurors probably would be allowed to return to bookstores, although it's a 
safe assumption that Ito will admonish them to stay away from the splashy book 
about Simpson's slain ex-wife that shut down jury selection for two days last 
month. 
</P>
<P>
 The viewing of edited television programs was made possible after the 
television networks agreed to prepare and produce the tapes.  
</P>
<P>
 "Our office contacted the networks at the request of the judge and they all 
responded favorably," said Suzanne Childs, spokeswoman for Dist. Atty. Gil 
Garcetti. Childs emphasized that the agreement is tentative. 
</P>
<P>
 Earlier this week, Ito said in open court that he was thinking of letting the 
jury watch public television's "MacNeil/Lehrer" program after Times' television 
critic Howard Rosenberg reported that the show does not do Simpson stories. But 
not a single juror expressed interest in such high-brow fare. Shows jury 
members do want to watch are "Star Trek," "Melrose Place," "Living Single," 
"Martin," "Roseanne," "Home Improvement," "Northern Exposure," "SeaQuest," "The 
Cosby Mysteries," "John Laroquette," "ER," "Sisters," "All My Children," "60 
Minutes" and football. 
</P>
<P>
 Ito and the lawyers met Friday to discuss modifying the order. The list of TV 
shows was compiled after jurors told Ito in writing Thursday what programs they 
miss most.  
</P>
<P>
 Joining Chapman and Ito in Friday's discussion was Deputy Dist. Atty. William 
Hodgman. Chapman emerged from the meeting and said the defense also wanted to 
relieve the jurors of the burden of the media ban. 
</P>
<P>
 Ito and the lawyers tentatively agreed that the jurors may watch sports on 
regular television, Chapman said, with the exception of ESPN, the all-sports 
cable network, which has offered regular coverage of the Simpson case. 
</P>
<P>
 "Having sports taped and watched later is not the same," she said.  
</P>
<P>
 The modified order will apply only to the 12 jurors and not the more than 80 
people who are scheduled to be in court Tuesday to begin the selection of 15 
alternate jurors, Chapman said. A more restrictive media ban is likely to be 
placed on that pool of potential alternates, she added. The Simpson Jury Here 
are thumbnail sketches and the seating chart for the 12 men and women chosen to 
determine the fate of football star and murder defendant O.J. Simpson. Seat 7 
38-year-old black woman Residence: Inglewood Job: Employment interviewer 
Reaction to Simpson's arrest: "Shocked." Opinion of Simpson now: "All I'm aware 
of is he's been charged with a crime. Any of ourselves might find ourselves in 
such a predicament, not necessarily making us criminals." * 
</P>
<P>
 Seat 8 38-year-old black woman Residence: Inglewood Job: Environmental health 
specialist Reaction: "I was shocked." Opinion of Simpson now: Neutral. "He 
states that he is innocent of the crimes charged against him and wants to prove 
this in a court of law." * 
</P>
<P>
 Seat 9 52-year-old black woman Residence: South-Central Los Angeles Job: Post 
office clerk Reaction: "Hurt." Opinion of Simpson now: Neutral. * 
</P>
<P>
 Seat 10 38-year-old Latino woman Residence: Norwalk Job: Letter carrier 
Reaction: "Don't recall." Opinion of Simpson now: "Don't know." * 
</P>
<P>
 Seat 11 22-year-old white woman Residence: Burbank Job: Property claims worker 
Reaction: "Shocked" Opinion of Simpson now: Neutral. * 
</P>
<P>
 Seat 12 46-year-old black man Residence: Long Beach Job: Courier Reaction: 
"Surprised." Opinion of Simpson now: Neutral. * 
</P>
<P>
 Front row Seat 1 50-year-old black woman Residence: South-Central Los Angeles 
Job: Vendor Reaction upon hearing Simpson was a suspect: "Stressful, sick 
feeling." Opinion of Simpson now: "I have the same feelings I had before he was 
accused. I respect him as an individual based on his past accomplishments." * 
</P>
<P>
 Seat 2 25-year-old black woman Residence: View Park Job: airline flight 
attendant Reaction: "I don't really know much about O.J. Simpson or the case so 
I don't really react to it." Opinion of Simpson now: "He is innocent until 
proven guilty. I don't know enough about him to give an opinion." * 
</P>
<P>
 Seat 3 52-year-old native American/white man Residence: Glendale Job: Teacher 
Reaction: "Shock" Simpson:"Neutral -- I don't know him as a person." * 
</P>
<P>
 Seat 4 32-year-old Latino man Residence: East Los Angeles Job: Truck driver 
Reaction: "How could a man who had it all be a suspect?" Opinion of Simpson 
now: "I think he was a great football player." * 
</P>
<P>
 Seat 5 37-year-old black woman Residence: Bellflower Job: Postal worker 
Reaction: "Wondered why, if so." Opinion of Simpson now: "Neutral. I've never 
followed football. I've only seen him mostly on commercials and the movies." * 
</P>
<P>
 Seat 6 48-year-old black man Residence: Inglewood Job: Quality control for 
Hertz Reaction: "I just didn't believe it." Opinion of Simpson now: Neutral. 
"No comment." Source: Jury questionnaires Researched by Times Staff Writer 
RALPH FRAMMOLINO 
</P>
