<DATE>
<P>
November 5, 1994, Saturday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 15; Column 1; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
253 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PREP EXTRA: SATURDAY FOOTBALL PULLOUT; SEA VIEW LEAGUE; JARRETT TAKES THREE 
TIPS TO GET EL TORO A VICTORY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOE WOJCIECHOWSKI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 El Toro's Jason Jarrett knew it was possible to win a game on a last-second 
desperation pass, but he just didn't believe it was possible Friday night with 
El Toro trailing Woodbridge and the ball sitting at the Chargers' 37 yard-line 
with 10 seconds left. 
</P>
<P>
 Jarrett became a believer after he caught a pass from Brian Wilson that had 
been tipped three times and raced the final 15 yards to give El Toro a 30-28 
victory in a Sea View League game at Trabuco Hills High School. 
</P>
<P>
 "The coaches diagramed the play before we went in and told me to wait for the 
tip," Jarrett said. "But I thought, 'This can't happen.' " 
</P>
<P>
 The play was the perfect ending for a game that featured big and wild plays. 
</P>
<P>
 After El Toro took a 14-0 lead, an advantage Charger Coach Mike Milner said he 
hoped would "take the life out of them." Woodbridge didn't roll over and give 
up, however. 
</P>
<P>
 Woodbridge's Carl Howard ran 33 yards on a reverse to pull the Warriors to 
within seven. And they tied the score after John Meineke returned an El Toro 
fumble to the two and Casey Harris snuck in for the touchdown two plays later. 
</P>
<P>
 The Chargers appeared to put the game out of reach when Jamie Hanaway ran 19 
yards for the touchdown. Woodbridge again bounced right back, however, when 
Theo Wakefield ran 56 yards on the Warriors' first play from scrimmage to make 
it 24-21. 
</P>
<P>
 Woodbridge then took the lead when an El Toro punt was batted the ball into 
the hands of Nate Perrizo who ran 56 yards untouched to make the score 28-24. 
JOE WOJCIECHOWSKI 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Game Story; Prep Sports 
</P>
